The project received initial approval by the ministry of Foreign Affairs on 28th June 2012 for a total amount of 64% of the proposed budget at the time of submission in March 2012. ZOA was then asked to submit a revised project plan by latest 15th September 2012. The Ministry decided on the revised plan on 16th November 2012, after which ZOA started further implementation of the project. ZOA found it best to not start the revised project immediately after submission in September 2012 so not to run the risk of beginning project work on a wrong footing, we considered the operational risks of starting the project without having received the donor’s ultimate directions, too high. Therefore, we could only start full project preparations in second half of November and were left with six weeks in 2012 to this effect. The extent of project activity in 2012 has been limited; work has focused on project preparations mainly. (Actual operations took off in 2013.)

This project describes the activities as carried out by ZOA, contributing to the Dutch Consortium for Rehabilitation (DCR) programme. DCR has the overall mission to contribute to the recovery of post-conflict societies in Africa by rehabilitating physical, societal and economic infrastructure in conflict-affected communities and assisting civil society actors to become stronger stakeholders in the creation of a sustainable peace dividend.

By 2025, through engagement with public authorities (formal and informal powerholders), men, women and youth with disabilities and other excluded groups, through resilient and capable local CSOs/DPOs in this fragile and conflict-affected country, are successfully influencing laws, policies, practices and norms for improved food security for all.

The We are able! program targets people (including women, men, and youth) with a disability, while, as spin-off, the program will also create opportunities for other excluded groups,3 such as vulnerable women, persons affected by leprosy, youth in general, excluded ethnic groups, internally displaced persons (IDPs) and refugees, as much as possible or necessary in the specific context. Intersectional traits often make people particularly vulnerable. Refugees with disabilities or disabled women and men of particular ethnic backgrounds often face the most severe forms of food insecurity. We are able! identifies and targets groups and individuals with particular vulnerabilities while creating synergies that allow others to benefit as well.

This activity covers the ZOA implementation under the Afghanistan Joint Response III, which is a programme funded by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs through the Dutch Relief Alliance (DRA), a cooperation of Dutch international organizations. This activity is funded through Cordaid, lead agency for this Joint Response.

ZOA proposes this Promoting Human Security in Ruzizi Valley Programme, to enhance stability and security in the border area between Burundi and the DRC as preconditions for people to rebuild their lives and livelihoods and contribute to structural poverty reduction. The programme will contribute to legitimate government, build local government capacity and will create a visible peace dividend.
This is a project by ZOA Sudan implemented under the ARC consortium programme named Enhancing stability through community resilience in Sudan
This is a project by ZOA Ethiopia implemented under the ARC consortium programme named Hope and Opportunities for the People in Ethiopia.
In this programme ZOA will contribute to enhance stability and safety as preconditions for people to rebuild their lives and strengthen their livelihood strategies.

Since March 2015, Yemen has been devastated by conflict, leaving 18.8 million people in need of humanitarian and protection assistance including 10.3 million in acute need. This activity covers the ZOA implementation under the Yemen Joint Response III, which is a programme funded by the Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs through the Dutch Relief Alliance (DRA), a cooperation of Dutch international organizations. This activity is funded through Care NL, lead agency for this Joint Response
